Building a Sentiment Analysis Pipeline¶

A common use case for text analytics is to use sentiment analysis. The growth of digital channels and options for data collection have expanded the ways that companies can monitor consumer sentiment and brand reputation.

Extracting insight from unstructured text data is one of the most valuable, but often challenging, tasks for organizations big and small. In this project, you have been assigned the task of collecting, processing, analyzing, and storing large amounts of text data to derive insight about your brand and competitors.

Your task is to build a text analytics sentiment analysis pipeline to use Python to extract, transform, load, and analyze Twitter data about five companies in a given industry. (Note it is not uncommon to encounter text analytics pipelines will use an extract-load-transform pipeline, with load coming before transform, to extract and load raw text into storage and then transform and analyze it on the way "out" of storage).

You should prepare a Jupyter notebook that contains all necessary code as well as Markdown text to explain each step of the process below, how it works, and what is happening. You will save the notebook as an HTML report and submit it to Canvas. The script should run without errors. You should use tables and/or visualizations to show your results. There should not be any long raw output printed to the page such as the raw response from the API.

    return requests.get(url = url,
            auth=bearer_oauth,
            params=params,
            timeout=timeout)

def retrive_tweets(company):
    ### Set base URL and use requests library to issue get request
    # GET /2/tweets/search/recent
    # The recent search endpoint returns Tweets from the last seven days that match a search query.
    url = "https://api.twitter.com/2/tweets/search/recent"
    max_results = 100
    param = {"query": f'{company}',
                     "max_results": max_results}
    r = getTweets(url, param)
    return r.json()

# text processing and cleaning
def process_tweets(t):
    
    t = t.lower()
    t = re.sub("@[A-Za-z0-9]+", "", t) # remove handles
    t = re.sub("#[A-Za-z0-9]+", "", t) # remove hashtags
    t = re.sub(r"http\S+", "", t)      # remove links (anything that doesn't have a space after http)
    t = re.sub(r"www.\S+", "", t)      # remove links
    t = re.sub("[()!?]", "", t)        # remove punctuation
    t = re.sub("\[.*?\]", "", t)       # remove puncutation
    t = re.sub("[^a-z]", " ", t)
    return t

# A helper function to generate a string of words with punctuations removed 
def word_str_generator(d):
    # initialize a new set to store all the single words from positive text reviews
    all_words_str = ""
    for column_name, s in d.iteritems():
        if s is not None:
            # split the current sentence
            temp_res = s.str.split()
            # append each word to the string with sapce as a seperator
            for w in temp_res:
                if w:
                    all_words_str = (" ").join(w)

    return all_words_str

# A helper function to display a wordcloud
def word_cloud_generator(s):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(background_color="white", width = 1000, height = 500).generate(s)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.savefig("your_file_name"+".png", bbox_inches='tight')
    plt.show()
    plt.close()

In [32]:
# a helper function for getting n-grams
def get_ngrams(text, ngram_from=2, ngram_to=2, n=None, max_features=20000):
    
    vec = CountVectorizer(ngram_range = (ngram_from, ngram_to), 
                          max_features = max_features, 
                          stop_words='english').fit(text)
    bag_of_words = vec.transform(text)
    sum_words = bag_of_words.sum(axis = 0) 
    words_freq = [(word, sum_words[0, i]) for word, i in vec.vocabulary_.items()]
    words_freq = sorted(words_freq, key = lambda x: x[1], reverse = True)
   
    return words_freq[:n]

# a helper function to vectorize the raw text
def vectorize(d, gram_name, ngram_from=1, ngram_to=1, n = 5):
    unigrams = get_ngrams(d.squeeze(), ngram_from, ngram_to, n)
    unigrams_df = pd.DataFrame(unigrams)
    unigrams_df.columns=[gram_name, "Frequency"]
    return unigrams_df.head()

Emotion Classification¶

In [59]:
# helper function for emotion recognition
def emotion_recog(text):
    import re
    import pandas as pd
    from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelWithLMHead
    import torch
    import sentencepiece

    # Extract the tokenizer from this model on Hugging Face Model Hub (will download first time you run it)
    tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained("mrm8488/t5-base-finetuned-emotion")

    # Extract the body from this model on Hugging Face Model Hub (will download first time you run it)
    model = AutoModelWithLMHead.from_pretrained("mrm8488/t5-base-finetuned-emotion")
    
    # Generate sequence of tensors (akin to multidimensional arrays) for input text
    inputs = tokenizer.encode(text,
                              return_tensors = "pt")
    
    # Generates sequences of token ids for models with a language modeling head. 
    outputs = model.generate(input_ids = inputs,
                             max_length = 2)
    
    # Extract the emotion classification decoded output
    decoded = [tokenizer.decode(ids) for ids in outputs]
    
    # Extract just the emotion label, remove padding
    emotion_label = decoded[0]
    label = re.sub(f".", "", emotion_label, count = 6)
    
    return label

The above text analysis techniques can be used to achieve many business goals. For example, customer reviews using text analysis will add value to the product. Through results of text analysis, sellers will know where their product did bad, where to improve the product and how to make the reviews become more positive. They can also know which product is the most popular so they would know how many to produce and don't need to set a fixed number and support the block chain become more smooth. Customer reviews can help customers learn more about the product and determine whether it is suitable for them. Customer reviews should provide customers with real product feedback from other shoppers.

Question 6¶

Explain how this sentiment analysis pipeline could be useful for (1) marketing analytics; (2) customer analytics; and (3) finance analytics (e.g. monitoring stock market trends).¶

1) Marketing Analytics - The sentiment analysis pipeline may be useful for marketing analysis because it is very suitable for market research and brand reputation monitoring. When companies conduct market research, sentiment analysis will enable them to understand customers' attitudes towards their products. Marketing data comes from different sources in various formats: website participation, CRM, email chain, in store system, click stream, social media data, etc. The analysis pipline solves the complex problem of unifying and standardizing these data, making it easy to analyze and measure customer participation across channels.

2) Customer Analytics - The sentiment analysis for customer reviews allows both the business itself and their potential customers can see an overview of whats good, whats lacking. Customer sentiment analysis can help the brand in a more feasible way. It can pick out which customers need additional care from a large number of feedback. They may mention issues such as payment, repeated frustration with call centers, or plans to cancel services. Tracking such topics and introducing the required processes is the key to closing the cycle: from receiving feedback to determining which actions will lead to a positive customer experience.

3) Finance Analytics - The financial analysis sentiment analysis pipeline is very important for the stock market, because the stock market often reacts to key events in the world. Today, it is not uncommon for key events to be first reported on social media, rather than by news organizations. In other words, investors can quickly obtain first-hand business intelligence through sentiment analysis channels. In addition, the rise and fall of the stock market largely depends on the confidence of investors and consumers. If the sentiment analysis pipeline is used, social media can become an excellent platform for in-depth understanding of consumer confidence.
